  "text": "Internal migration, understood as a change in usual residence within a country, is a much more common event than other demographic phenomena such as death or birth, especially with secular fertility decline. In the mid-2000s, the median Aggregate Crude Migration Intensity (ACMI), a measure of all permanent changes of address within a country, was 7.5% for 1-year period in a range of 45 countries around the world [CITATION_1] , and this excludes international migrations which are estimated at only 0.12% a year, i.e. 60 times less than internal migration [CITATION_2] . To give a sense of scale, the world crude birth rate was only 2% a year and the world crude death rate less than 1% (United Nations Population Division, 2014). Across the 45 selected countries for which data were available, only four had an 1-year ACMI smaller than 2% [CITATION_3] .",
